      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i keep getting a 500 error on our /api/v1/checkout/process endpoint whenever a user tries to apply a discount code. i've attached the partial logs below but it's super intermittent. can u see what's up?\n\n[2023-10-27 14:22:01] ERROR: Internal Server Error - RequestID: 8829-xf2\n[2023-10-27 14:22:01] STACKTRACE: Unhandled exception in DiscountService.apply(DiscountObject dto)\n[2023-10-27 14:22:01] java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke \"com.store.models.Coupon.getExpiryDate()\" because \"coupon\" is null\n[2023-10-27 14:22:02] ERROR: Internal Server Error - RequestID: 8830-xf4\n[2023-10-27 14:22:02] STACKTRACE: Unhandled exception in DiscountService.apply(DiscountObject dto)\n[2023-10-27 14:22:02] java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke \"com.store.models.Coupon.getExpiryDate()\" because \"coupon\" is null",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The logs reveal a classic \"null pointer\" issue, but the intermittent nature of your 500 errors suggests a race condition or a timing issue where the discount code is being fetched before the cache is fully populated. You should add a null check for the `coupon` object before calling `getExpiryDate()`, or perhaps implement a retry mechanism with exponential backoff to handle the transient state. If the database is the culprit, consider adding a `@Cacheable` annotation to your service method to avoid hitting the DB on every request.\n\nI also recommend checking your application server's thread pool size, as a high volume of requests might be starving the threads responsible for fetching discount data. If the problem persists, you might want to enable the \"verbose\" logging mode to see if the error happens during the initial fetch or after the code is retrieved.\n\nFinally, don't forget to add a proper error response in your controller that tells the user their code is invalid or expired instead of just returning a generic 500 error.",
      "source": "target",
